    <header class="mb-8">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-serif mb-4">We Three Sang a Song in Honour of May at Her Cork Gravestone</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-stone-600 dark:text-gray-400">
            Based on a column by John Arnold, published in the Echo, 7 May 2026
        </p>
    </header>

    <figure class="my-8">
        <img src="{{ '/assets/imgs/may-higgins-headstone-echolive.jpg' | url }}"
             alt="Pat White, John Arnold and Charlie McAllister at the Higgins headstone in Templecurraheen Graveyard"
             class="w-full max-w-2xl mx-auto rounded-lg shadow-lg">
        <figcaption class="text-center text-sm text-stone-600 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">
            The &ldquo;we three&rdquo; at the Higgins headstone: Pat White, John Arnold and Charlie McAllister gathered to sing in honour of Mai Higgins (n&eacute;e Carew),
            who is buried at Templecurraheen alongside her husband Michael (Micky) Higgins.
            <br>Photograph courtesy of the Echo.
        </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif mt-10 mb-4">A simple headstone on an East Cork hillside</h2>

    <p>
        Writing in the Echo on the occasion of the unveiling of the new Cork County Council information board at
        Templecurraheen, columnist John Arnold turned his attention to a quiet headstone in the graveyard &mdash; the resting
        place of Michael Higgins, who died in 1974, and his wife Mai, who passed away in 2009.
    </p>

    <p>
        Six years ago, Arnold writes, Templecurraheen &mdash; set high on a hillside in the parish of Carrigtwohill &mdash; was
        in a sorry state. Like many other ancient burial grounds, the place was uneven and dangerous to traverse.
        A church once stood here, said to have been burned by the forces of Oliver Cromwell in the early 1650s, and not
        far away stand the gaunt remains of a famine workhouse, with a huge famine burial pit still visible at the back
        of the graveyard.
    </p>

    <p>
        It was local man <strong>Michael Finn</strong> who singularly took on the task of clearing and cleaning this sacred ground.
        Arnold borrows a line that Robert Kennedy was fond of quoting from George Bernard Shaw &mdash; <em>"Some men see things as they
        are, and ask why. I dream of things that never were, and ask why not."</em> &mdash; and applies it to Mick Finn, whose
        dream came to fruition on the Monday of the unveiling, when a few hundred people gathered in glorious sunshine
        to see the burial ground transformed into a well-kept place of serenity and beauty.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif mt-10 mb-4">May Carew of Dungarvan &mdash; Mai Higgins of Templecurraheen</h2>

    <p>
        Among the stones Michael Finn brought back into the light was one to Michael Higgins and his wife Mai. Sometimes
        called May Higgins, and sometimes Mai &Oacute; Higgins, her name carried a special resonance for anyone who ever
        listened to <em>F&aacute;ilte Isteach</em>, the Saturday-night RT&Eacute; radio programme presented by the great
        Donncha &Oacute; D&uacute;laing. Many of the songs Donncha played &mdash; <em>Sweet Youghal Bay</em>, <em>Gweebarra Bay</em>,
        <em>Beautiful Bundoran</em> &mdash; were written by this Waterford lady.
    </p>

    <p>
        Growing up in Dungarvan and Old Parish, young May Carew had a fascination for water &mdash; the sea, rivers, lakes &mdash;
        and penned many beautiful songs with a maritime theme. She met Garda Michael Higgins of Knockraha when he called
        to the Garda Station in Dungarvan and asked her to accompany him to a Garda dance. She said yes, and their love
        story began. While the couple were honeymooning, she wrote <em>Moonlight On The River Shannon</em>.
    </p>

    <p>
        Though the Higgins family lived in Dublin for many years, May&rsquo;s native Decies was never far from her mind.
        <em>The Silvery Sands of Tramore</em>, <em>Comeragh&rsquo;s Rugged Hills</em>, and <em>The Cross of Old Piltown</em>
        all reflected her love for home. Perhaps her best-known composition, widely recorded, is
        <em>Dungarvan My Home Town</em> &mdash; truly a Waterford anthem. John Arnold notes that he has found more than
        fifty songs written by Mai Higgins.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif mt-10 mb-4">A connection to Gortroe</h2>

    <p>
        Arnold&rsquo;s own connection to Templecurraheen came through another grave entirely. In 1834, in his home parish
        of Bartlemy, twelve men were shot and killed at the Widow Ryan&rsquo;s farmyard in what became known as the
        <a href="{{ '/stories/massacre-at-gortroe/' | url }}" class="text-primary-700 hover:text-primary-900 dark:text-purple-400 dark:hover:text-purple-300">Battle of Gortroe</a>.
        Among the dead were two brothers, <a href="{{ '/stories/the-collins-brothers-of-templecurraheen/' | url }}" class="text-primary-700 hover:text-primary-900 dark:text-purple-400 dark:hover:text-purple-300">John and Michael Collins</a>,
        sons of the widow Mrs Collins, who were brought back to Templecurraheen on 21 December 1834 to be buried with
        their father.
    </p>

    <p>
        For 150 years the actual location of their grave was lost. When a monument was erected at Gortroe in 1984,
        Paddy Healy &mdash; a relative of the family &mdash; could only place their wreath inside the graveyard gate. During
        the great clean-up, Mick Finn found the old, sunken Collins headstone, raised it, re-lettered it, and at long
        last added the names of John and Michael. Arnold was present last year when that stone was unveiled and
        blessed, and has returned many times since.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif mt-10 mb-4">Three voices on the hillside</h2>

    <p>
        At the unveiling, Arnold was thrilled to meet an old friend, Dungarvan native <strong>Charlie McAllister</strong> &mdash;
        a great Gael, referee, and gorgeous singer who had once met May at a concert in their native town. He also
        met veteran c&eacute;il&iacute; musician and singer <strong>Pat White</strong>, a life-long admirer of Mai Higgins who
        had known her in Dublin and who honours her memory by keeping her songs alive.
    </p>

    <p>
        Together, the three of them &mdash; Pat, Charlie, and John &mdash; stood on the East Cork hillside above the Lee and
        Cork Harbour and sang, in honour of May, at her gravestone. As Arnold writes, her final resting place
        on that hillside surely makes her soul happy, looking out over the harbour she would have loved.
    </p>

